  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Drafting Logic Begins**\n\nOkay, I\'m starting to draft the heart failure detection business logic now. I\'m focusing on the heart failure dataset\'s schema from Kaggle. I\'ve begun to list out the columns: Age, Sex, ChestPainType, RestingBP, Cholesterol, and so on. This is where I\'ll begin to build detection.\n\n\n**Detailing Key Features**\n\nNow I\'m diving deeper into the dataset features to build the model. I\'ve categorized the attributes. I\'m focusing on refining the feature list: chest pain type, resting blood pressure, cholesterol, fasting blood sugar, electrocardiogram results, maximum heart rate achieved, exercise-induced angina, oldpeak, ST segment slope, and the target variable, heart disease. The aim is a high-fidelity diagnostic model, with standard clinical formulas in mind.\n\n\n**Integrating AI Insights**\n\nI\'m now integrating AI insights with the existing clinical rules. The goal is to provide instantaneous results using the rule-based approach on either the frontend or backend. Simultaneously, I want Gemini 3.5 to analyze the findings and offer an AI-generated interpretation. I\'m focusing on supporting bulk uploads, leveraging the rule-based model for rapid processing and allowing AI-powered in-depth analysis on selected records. I\'m working on a fully typed patient model in TypeScript now.\n\n\n**Designing Prediction Endpoint**\n\nI\'m now designing the `/api/predict` endpoint, envisioning a rule-based baseline probability calculation. Then I will integrate Gemini for detailed clinical reports and diagnostic checklists, evaluating the robustness.\nI\'m also preparing for the mathematical component.\n\n\n**Refining Prediction Model**\n\nI\'m now refining the prediction algorithm. I\'m focusing on incorporating statistical insights from the Kaggle dataset to enhance prediction realism and align with machine learning findings. Key insights have emerged from feature importance and correlation analysis. For instance, the ST_Slope Down or Flat and ExerciseAngina (Yes) are strong indicators, with chest pain type, oldpeak values, and max heart rate providing additional critical factors. The age and sex also weigh heavily into predictions.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the `/src/types.ts` file to define the types for patients, records, statistics, and prediction results. This ensures strict typings throughout our modular full-stack code."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 870939790
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
